Chazz Reinhold is not a kook.

16:36.829 --> 16:39.373
He is a brave and a decent man.
He is a pioneer.

16:39.540 --> 16:42.584
He lived with his mother till he was 40.
She tried to poison his oatmeal.

16:42.752 --> 16:46.421
Erroneous! Erroneous.
Erroneous on both counts.

16:46.589 --> 16:49.091
-Oh, Lord. Here we go again.
-What you should be worried about...

16:49.258 --> 16:51.885
...is not Chazz Reinhold,
who's in the hall of fame.

16:52.053 --> 16:54.763
What you should be worried about
is you're getting sloppy.

16:54.931 --> 16:57.974
Now, if you sit there
and expect me to go out on a limb...

16:58.142 --> 17:01.103
...and try to pull off
the greatest crash of all time...

17:01.270 --> 17:03.438
...I gotta know that your head's right.

17:05.108 --> 17:07.776
There is no room for error.

17:07.944 --> 17:10.278
Secret Service. Consequences.

17:11.280 --> 17:13.031
I love your enthusiasm.

17:13.199 --> 17:15.951
If I do this, I don't wanna half-ass it.

17:16.119 --> 17:17.619
I want it well planned.

17:17.787 --> 17:19.913
He's back.

17:20.081 --> 17:22.249
All right, partner.
We'll start scheming tonight, okay?

17:22.417 --> 17:24.876
-Sounds good. Okay.
-If you need me, I'll be on line six.

17:30.717 --> 17:31.883
Could be fun.

17:43.646 --> 17:44.646
Wow

17:44.814 --> 17:47.149
KATHLEEN: Mr. Senator. Thank you.
-Congratulations, Kathleen.

17:47.316 --> 17:49.192
-Bill, congratulations.
-Thank you, senator.

17:49.360 --> 17:51.319
Secretary, they just grow up
so damn fast.

17:51.487 --> 17:52.612
That's the truth, yeah.

17:52.780 --> 17:57.617
-Okay. Let's do our pregame.
-What do you got?

17:57.785 --> 18:00.579
Articles on Secretary Cleary's
economic policies.

18:00.747 --> 18:04.249
There's also a roster of key family members,
a glossary, sailing terms.

18:04.417 --> 18:06.209
-Sailing?
-Sailing's like sex to these people.

18:06.377 --> 18:08.837
-They love it.
-Harvard, Kennedy School of Government.

18:09.005 --> 18:11.465
Mom's big with charities,
blah, blah, blah.

18:11.632 --> 18:13.133
Three daughters, one son.

18:13.301 --> 18:15.594
-I get it. Good work.
-Good.

18:16.137 --> 18:18.138
[CHATTERING]

18:31.277 --> 18:32.819
Let me see that again, please.

18:33.279 --> 18:35.614
Pretty handsome.

18:35.782 --> 18:37.491
Okay, what's our back-story?

18:37.658 --> 18:40.827
We're brothers from New Hampshire,
we're venture capitalists.

18:40.995 --> 18:42.871
JEREMY:
I'm sick of that.

18:43.039 --> 18:46.833
Let's be from Vermont, and let's have
an emerging maple-syrup conglomerate.

18:47.001 --> 18:49.544
Wait, that's stupid. We don't know
anything about maple syrup.

18:49.712 --> 18:51.797
I know everything there is
to know about maple syrup.

18:51.964 --> 18:53.965
I love maple syrup.
I love maple syrup on pancakes.

18:54.133 --> 18:56.802
I love it on pizza.
I put a little bit in my hair...

18:56.969 --> 18:59.012
...when I've had a rough week.
What do you think holds it up, slick?

18:59.180 --> 19:01.890
The first quarter of the big game
and you wanna toss up a Hail Mary.

19:02.058 --> 19:04.434
I'd like to be pimps from Oakland
or cowboys from Arizona...

19:04.602 --> 19:08.230
...but it's not Halloween.
Grow up, Peter Pan. Count Chocula.

19:08.397 --> 19:10.148
Look, we've been to a million weddings.

19:10.316 --> 19:12.400
And guess what.
We've rocked them all.

19:19.492 --> 19:20.909
Great day.

19:21.077 --> 19:23.328
- [WHISPERING] The Eagle has landed.
JEREMY: The big show.

19:23.496 --> 19:26.873
Hey, hey. Fifth row back
with the fancy hat.

19:27.041 --> 19:29.376
I like that.

19:29.544 --> 19:32.879
No, don't waste your time on girls
with hats, they tend to be very proper.

19:34.173 --> 19:35.382
JEREMY:
Yeah?

19:35.550 --> 19:38.426
The proper girl in the hat
just eye-fucked the shit out of me.

19:39.679 --> 19:42.013
JOHN:
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

19:42.181 --> 19:46.017
Why don't you say it a little louder?
I don't think the priest heard you.

19:46.185 --> 19:48.895
Look, John,
I'm sorry I'm not sorry, okay?

19:49.063 --> 19:50.939
I'm not gonna apologize.
I'm a cocksman.

19:52.942 --> 19:55.735
JOHN: Tourette's.
-Frank Myers.

19:55.903 --> 19:57.904
John Ryan.
Say hello to my brother, Jeremy.

19:58.072 --> 19:59.364
-Hi.
-How are you?

19:59.532 --> 20:01.908
So, um, how do you know the groom?

20:02.076 --> 20:04.536
We are Uncle Ned's kids.

20:04.704 --> 20:06.580
Uncle Ned.

20:06.747 --> 20:10.417
-Is he Liz's brother?
-Uncle Ned, the brother of Aunt Liz.

20:10.585 --> 20:12.085
How is everybody?

20:12.253 --> 20:14.588
Well, Dad kind of putters
around the house.

20:14.755 --> 20:17.007
Aunt Liz sends her best.
She couldn't make it.

20:17.800 --> 20:19.801
Yeah, I know.

20:20.011 --> 20:21.469
She's dead.

20:22.805 --> 20:24.472
From the grave.

20:24.640 --> 20:26.308
She sends her best from the grave.

20:26.475 --> 20:28.476
We've become extremely spiritual...

20:28.644 --> 20:30.812
-...ever since she passed.
-I see.

20:31.022 --> 20:33.148
But thank you so much
for your kindness, brother.

20:33.316 --> 20:35.817
Lord knows we need family now
more than ever.

20:35.985 --> 20:38.904
-Well, you're welcome.
JEREMY: Thank you.

20:39.071 --> 20:41.031
[PACHELBEL'S "CANON IN D"
PLAYS OVER SPEAKERS]

20:41.449 --> 20:43.491
How many times are you
gonna do this shit?

20:43.659 --> 20:45.952
Rule number 32:
You don't commit to a relative...

20:46.120 --> 20:48.580
...unless you're absolutely positive
that they have a pulse.

20:48.748 --> 20:50.957
Rule 1 6:
Give me an up-to-date family tree.

20:51.125 --> 20:53.126
Your mistake.
You made me look like an idiot.

20:53.294 --> 20:55.629
Rule number 76:
No excuses, play like a champion.

21:07.350 --> 21:09.184
Hello, Red.

21:11.646 --> 21:14.147
-Dibs.
-She's all yours.

21:16.192 --> 21:17.859
I ain't gonna fight you.

21:18.027 --> 21:20.028
[WAGNER'S "BRIDAL CHORUS"
PLAYS OVER SPEAKERS]

21:41.968 --> 21:43.718
I think we've got a crier.

21:43.886 --> 21:46.471
-No shot.
-Twenty bucks.

21:46.639 --> 21:48.682
-Make it 40.
-Done.

21:50.142 --> 21:51.893
[CRYING]

21:52.061 --> 21:53.895
Oh, are you kidding me?

21:54.063 --> 21:56.564
It's beautiful.
It's moving. It's a wedding.

21:56.732 --> 22:02.821
And now for our next reading,
I'd like to ask the bride's sister Gloria...

22:02.989 --> 22:04.864
...up to the lectern.

22:05.032 --> 22:06.825
Twenty bucks, 1 Corinthians.

22:06.993 --> 22:09.327
Double or nothing, Colossians 3: 1 2.

22:11.914 --> 22:15.166
And now a reading from
Paul's First Letter to the Corinthians.

22:15.334 --> 22:19.254
"Love is patient, love is kind."

22:19.422 --> 22:22.424
As you all know, Craig and Christina...

22:22.591 --> 22:25.552
...are quite the sailing enthusiasts.

22:25.720 --> 22:29.764
In that light, they have elected
to exchange vows...

22:29.932 --> 22:32.434
...which they themselves have written.

22:33.561 --> 22:35.270
The ring.

22:36.564 --> 22:37.939
CRAIG:
I, Craig...

22:38.107 --> 22:40.692
...take you, Christina, to be my wife...

22:40.860 --> 22:44.112
...my best friend and my first mate...

22:44.280 --> 22:45.613
[SNICKERING]

22:46.032 --> 22:50.285
...through sickness and health,
clear skies and squalls.

22:50.453 --> 22:51.578
[GIGGLING]

22:51.954 --> 22:52.954
[CLAIRE CLEARS THROAT]

22:53.122 --> 22:54.914
I'm sorry, I have a tickle in my throat.

22:56.584 --> 22:59.627
CHRISTINA:
I, Christina, take you, Craig...

22:59.795 --> 23:01.880
...to be my best friend...

23:02.048 --> 23:04.174
...and my captain...

23:05.009 --> 23:08.261
...to be your anchor and your sail...

23:08.429 --> 23:09.804
Well, this is a first.

23:09.972 --> 23:12.432
CHRISTINA:
...your starboard and your port.

23:12.600 --> 23:13.641
[SNORTS]

23:13.809 --> 23:18.563
And now I pronounce you
husband and wife.

23:18.731 --> 23:20.648
You may kiss the first mate.

23:20.816 --> 23:22.150
[GIGGLES]

23:22.318 --> 23:24.319
[PEOPLE CHEERING]

23:24.487 --> 23:26.988
[MENDELSSOHN'S "WEDDING MARCH"
PLAYS OVER SPEAKERS]

23:28.157 --> 23:30.158
[LAUGHING]

23:46.967 --> 23:48.968
[BAND PLAYING SWING MUSIC]

24:04.693 --> 24:06.778
Sorry, just a sampler.

24:06.946 --> 24:09.489
-Told you this would be classy, right?
-Yes, you did.

24:09.657 --> 24:12.867
Class, first class all the way.
You were not lying.

24:13.035 --> 24:14.536
Class, class, class.

24:18.290 --> 24:21.334
They've got some kind of seasoning
on here. It must be sprinkled.

24:21.502 --> 24:24.796
Okay, go get us seats near,
but not too near, the bridal party.

24:24.964 --> 24:27.549
I'm gonna go drop this box
of fresh Wyoming air.

24:28.884 --> 24:31.177
If you see crab cakes,
get some because I love them.

24:31.345 --> 24:33.138
Consider it done.

24:37.685 --> 24:40.812
-Fondue set.
-Excuse me?

24:40.980 --> 24:43.731
The present you're holding is
a sterling-silver fondue set.

24:43.899 --> 24:47.068
-John Ryan.
-Claire Cleary.

24:47.236 --> 24:48.862
Uh, so how do you know that?

24:49.029 --> 24:51.322
Well, I'm a psychic.

24:51.490 --> 24:52.991
-You're psychic?
-I am.

24:53.159 --> 24:54.742
-Really?
-Yes.

24:55.536 --> 24:58.329
-What's that one?
-Knife set. German. Very nice.

24:58.497 --> 25:01.416
-Hm. And that?
-Cotton linens, Egyptian.

25:01.584 --> 25:02.625
Ooh.

25:02.793 --> 25:04.419
-What about that?
-Oh, I'll go all day.

25:04.587 --> 25:07.297
Place settings, candlesticks,
crystal stemware...

25:07.464 --> 25:10.717
...which they'll probably never use
because it's crystal stemware.

25:10.885 --> 25:13.428
-Okay, how about that?
-This?

25:13.762 --> 25:14.804
Uh....

25:14.972 --> 25:19.100
Massage oils and a book on tantra,
probably from the wacky aunt.

25:21.187 --> 25:22.896
Let's check.

25:24.190 --> 25:26.232
-Who's it from?
-Aunt Millie.

25:26.400 --> 25:29.110
-Yes!
-Well, you have a gift.

25:29.278 --> 25:32.405
I know. Unfortunately my powers only
apply to useless consumer products.

25:32.573 --> 25:37.118
Well, if the police are missing a Belgian
waffle maker, you could give them a hand.

25:37.453 --> 25:39.204
[CHUCKLING]

25:39.371 --> 25:41.289
-Claire, we need you for pictures.
-Oh, okay.

25:41.457 --> 25:43.541
-Who's your friend?
-This is John Ryan.

25:44.084 --> 25:46.628
-Hello.
-Excuse us.

25:49.965 --> 25:52.675
JEREMY: I might just have one more
of the samplers here.

25:52.843 --> 25:54.302
-Good.
-What have we got?

25:54.470 --> 25:56.596
Come back with some more stuff.
That's good, though.

25:56.764 --> 25:59.140
These bacon-wrapped scallops,
phenomenal.

25:59.808 --> 26:02.602
Really hit the spot. Unbelievable.

26:03.229 --> 26:06.606
Oh, shit. Isn't that the girl you hooked up
with at the Andersons' wedding?

26:09.818 --> 26:12.153
-Oh, Jesus, I'm smoked.
-No, no, don't panic.

26:12.321 --> 26:15.073
We're gonna do number 1 0
from the playbook. Here she comes.

26:15.241 --> 26:19.661
Shlomo? I thought you were renouncing
all your possessions and moving to Nepal.

26:20.829 --> 26:23.456
Shlomo, don't you remember me?

26:24.500 --> 26:26.501
JOHN:
Oh, my God, you didn't hear.

26:26.669 --> 26:30.171
I'm so sorry.
Shlomo had a scuba-diving accident.

26:30.965 --> 26:34.092
Yeah, he came up too fast
and the oxygen deprivation....

26:34.677 --> 26:37.387
Poor guy. He doesn't remember anyone,
even me, his own brother.

26:37.554 --> 26:39.514
I'm just some nice guy
who helps him out.

26:40.849 --> 26:42.100
You poor thing.

26:44.436 --> 26:46.938
He can't hear anything either.
It's part of the accident.

26:47.106 --> 26:48.690
So are you here
for the Clearys' wedding?

26:49.358 --> 26:52.860
Oh, yes. Yes, but I have to leave.

26:53.028 --> 26:55.405
-I've got a flight to Madrid.
JOHN: Oh, you have to leave?

26:55.572 --> 26:57.365
-Yes.
JOHN: Oh, okay.

26:58.158 --> 26:59.951
I could hang out for a few minutes.

27:02.830 --> 27:05.206
Oh, actually that won't be necessary.

27:05.374 --> 27:08.835
Shlomo would like me to take him to the
bathroom, then get him some crab cakes.

27:09.003 --> 27:10.837
So, yeah, no, that's not--

27:11.005 --> 27:12.297
Okay, okay.

27:12.464 --> 27:16.092
Okay, I'll take you to get crab cakes first,
then I'll take you to the bathroom.

27:17.428 --> 27:18.886
You know what?

27:19.054 --> 27:22.348
Here's my number.
If there is anything I can do to help....

27:22.516 --> 27:24.142
Okay.

27:24.310 --> 27:26.477
Okay, have a safe flight.
Don't worry about us.

27:26.645 --> 27:29.647
-We're gonna be fine, we're gonna make it.
-Okay.

27:30.899 --> 27:32.567
Doctor.

27:33.402 --> 27:35.153
She looked good.
I might give her a shout.

27:35.321 --> 27:36.904
How? She thinks you're deaf.

27:37.072 --> 27:40.366
Everyone wants to be part of a miracle.
I turned the corner, she's a part of it.

27:40.534 --> 27:42.368
People helping people.
It's powerful stuff.

27:42.536 --> 27:45.997
God, you're a sick man.
You also may be a genius.

27:46.165 --> 27:47.999
Okay, so, what angle
are we gonna play here?

27:48.167 --> 27:50.835
I'm gonna go with the balloon-animal
display for the kids...

27:51.003 --> 27:54.005
...and then when she comes to
check it out, guess who's a broken man.

27:54.173 --> 27:55.757
-Haunted past.
-Haunted past. Excellent.

27:55.924 --> 27:57.884
-How about you?
-I'll dance with the flower girl.

27:58.052 --> 28:00.011
Or be a charter member
of Oprah's Book Club.

28:00.179 --> 28:02.847
-It's all deadly. I'll see you in a little.
-Yes.

28:03.015 --> 28:06.142
Final touch. There it is.

28:06.310 --> 28:08.436
One happy elephant.

28:08.979 --> 28:11.606
All right. Who else wants something?

28:11.774 --> 28:13.149
I want a bicycle.

28:13.317 --> 28:17.111
A bicycle? Well, a bicycle,
that would take a lot of balloons...

28:17.279 --> 28:19.405
...and Uncle Jeremy's
a little tired right now...

28:19.573 --> 28:22.283
...so why don't we do something like,
let's say, a giraffe?

28:22.451 --> 28:24.535
I just want a bicycle!

28:27.331 --> 28:28.623
Why are you yelling at me?

28:28.791 --> 28:31.084
Whatever. Make me a bicycle, clown.

28:38.175 --> 28:41.594
I'm gonna make you a bicycle.
But I don't want to make you a bicycle.

28:41.762 --> 28:43.596
Shut your mouth, funny guy,
and make it.

28:46.517 --> 28:48.393
JOHN:
You got it.

28:49.812 --> 28:52.730
There you go. Yeah, you got it.

29:03.992 --> 29:05.952
Let's see how you do
with somebody your own age.

29:06.120 --> 29:08.371
I think I'm up to the challenge.

29:08.539 --> 29:10.289
All right, will you save me
a dance for later?

29:10.499 --> 29:13.668
-Maybe.
JOHN: Ha, ha. Okay.

29:17.798 --> 29:19.799
[CLEARS THROAT AND CHUCKLES]

29:25.514 --> 29:28.015
Go on, take it, you hyena.

29:28.684 --> 29:30.309
Don't say thank you.

29:30.519 --> 29:32.353
Hi. You're good.

29:32.521 --> 29:35.440
That thing? I'm just warming up.
Last week I did a...

29:35.607 --> 29:38.526
-...exact replica to scale of Wrigley Field.
-Ha, ha.

29:38.694 --> 29:41.028
Honest to God.
I don't have anywhere to put it.

29:41.196 --> 29:42.947
Okay, then I'll take a sports car.

29:43.699 --> 29:44.866
How about a dance?

29:45.033 --> 29:46.826
That's what I really wanted.

30:12.060 --> 30:14.061
[MUSIC ENDS
AND PEOPLE CLAPPING]

30:18.775 --> 30:21.152
So how long have you
and the secretary been married?

30:21.320 --> 30:23.863
-Thirty years next April.
-Oh, that's beautiful.

30:24.031 --> 30:26.491
Yeah, and we were faithful
for two of them.

30:28.076 --> 30:30.953
-Hm?
-Enjoy the party.

30:35.334 --> 30:37.793
-Congratulations, Mr. Secretary.
CLEARY: Thanks.

30:42.799 --> 30:44.592
Secretary Cleary, John Ryan.

30:44.760 --> 30:46.886
-Hi, John.
-I just wanted to tell you how much...

30:47.095 --> 30:50.890
...I enjoyed your position paper
on economic expansion in Micronesia.

30:51.600 --> 30:53.184
You've read my position paper?

30:53.352 --> 30:55.353
I read it while I was
sailing my boat to Bermuda.

30:55.521 --> 30:57.021
A sailor?

30:57.189 --> 30:59.941
-Good man, take a seat.
-Oh, thanks.

31:00.108 --> 31:02.193
You didn't happen to catch my speech...

31:02.361 --> 31:05.404
...on the Paraguayan debt
and money supply issue, did you?

31:05.572 --> 31:07.740
Are you kidding me?
I thought it was great.

31:07.908 --> 31:12.912
Your argument for the inverse ratio
of capitalization to debt was genius.

31:13.121 --> 31:16.290
Now, if we can just get Congress
not to be so shortsighted.

31:16.458 --> 31:20.628
Yes. Well put. "Shortsighted."

31:20.796 --> 31:25.299
John, what do you say you and I head out
to the deck and light up a couple of cigars?

31:25.467 --> 31:26.634
-Stogies?
-Yeah.

31:26.802 --> 31:28.052
Why not?

31:28.637 --> 31:31.806
It's just that we lost a lot
of really good men out there.

31:34.393 --> 31:35.977
I'm sorry.

31:36.144 --> 31:39.230
Gloria, I think I gotta
go get some fresh air.

31:40.357 --> 31:43.818
Thank you so much for the dance
and it was wonderful to meet you.

31:46.363 --> 31:48.614
I wish I were stronger.

31:55.080 --> 31:57.498
Jeremy!

31:58.709 --> 32:00.710
Jeremy, wait up!

32:04.172 --> 32:07.341
CLEARY: John, you seem like an astute man.
JOHN: Thank you.

32:07.509 --> 32:09.677
Maybe you can help
explain something to me.

32:10.095 --> 32:12.471
See that young man
out there on the dock?

32:12.973 --> 32:14.849
JOHN: Sure.
CLEARY: That's my son, Todd.

32:15.017 --> 32:18.436
Twenty-two years old,
the whole world in front of him.

32:18.604 --> 32:21.856
Every advantage in life,
advantages I never had.

32:22.024 --> 32:23.733
Well, that's not exactly true.

32:24.067 --> 32:27.361
He had the same advantages I had,
which is a hell of a lot of advantages.

32:27.529 --> 32:30.031
So here's my question:

32:30.407 --> 32:32.491
What's he got to be so morose about?

32:33.410 --> 32:35.286
Maybe he hasn't found
something to believe in.

32:35.454 --> 32:37.496
Oh, he says he believes in art.

32:37.873 --> 32:39.624
But all I've seen him do...

32:39.791 --> 32:43.878
...is dribble his own blood on a canvas
and smear it around with a stick.

32:44.046 --> 32:46.714
-You know, some people call that art.
-It's crap.

32:47.466 --> 32:51.886
What about having a public service,
an obligation to our fellow man?

32:52.763 --> 32:54.305
Well, maybe he's....

32:54.473 --> 32:56.849
Maybe he's just trying to find
his own way, his own path.

32:57.017 --> 32:59.352
I mean, you cast a pretty big shadow.

33:02.272 --> 33:03.814
Yeah.

33:04.608 --> 33:07.610
Yeah. Yeah, perhaps...

33:07.778 --> 33:10.321
...I should take it easier on him.

33:10.489 --> 33:11.530
Perhaps.

33:11.948 --> 33:14.909
Death, you are my bitch lover!

33:16.953 --> 33:18.496
CLEARY:
Todd, that's good!

33:19.581 --> 33:20.998
Tell that mean ocean!

33:23.001 --> 33:24.710
Oh, see that?

33:25.295 --> 33:27.129
It's a start.

33:28.131 --> 33:30.675
GLORIA:
So you dove into the icy water?

33:30.842 --> 33:35.763
Why would a man risk his own life
for the life of a complete stranger?

33:35.931 --> 33:38.724
The great 1 9th century philosopher
Schopenhauer...

33:39.393 --> 33:44.146
...he said, at that moment, when a human
sees another human in danger...

33:44.523 --> 33:48.567
...that there's this breaking in
of metaphysical awareness.

33:49.319 --> 33:51.570
Do you know what
that awareness is, Gloria?

33:51.738 --> 33:54.281
-What?
-That we're all one.

33:55.200 --> 33:59.453
That separateness is an illusion.

34:00.414 --> 34:02.331
And that I'm one with everyone.

34:02.499 --> 34:06.961
With the prime minister of England
and my cousin Harry.

34:07.629 --> 34:09.714
You and me.

34:10.006 --> 34:11.966
The fat kid from What's Happening!!

34:12.634 --> 34:14.343
The Olsen twins.

34:14.511 --> 34:16.262
Natalie Portman.

34:16.430 --> 34:18.931
The guy who wrote Catcher in the Rye.

34:19.266 --> 34:21.142
Nat King Cole.

34:21.309 --> 34:22.393
Carrot Top.

34:23.228 --> 34:24.812
Jay-Z.

34:24.980 --> 34:26.897
-"Weird Al" Yankovic.
-Hm.

34:27.315 --> 34:29.650
Harry Potter, if he existed.

34:29.943 --> 34:31.402
The whore on the street corner.

34:31.987 --> 34:33.320
Your mother.

34:33.780 --> 34:36.115
-We're all one.
-We are?

34:36.283 --> 34:38.075
That my hands are your hands.

34:38.243 --> 34:39.285
Oh.

34:39.453 --> 34:41.620
And that my cheek...

34:42.289 --> 34:44.498
...is really your cheek.

34:45.667 --> 34:46.917
And that my lips....

34:47.335 --> 34:48.753
Are my lips.

34:48.920 --> 34:52.339
According to Mr. Schopenhauer,
they are.

34:53.175 --> 34:55.176
[GLORIA MOANING]

34:55.844 --> 34:57.845
CLEARY:
Well, the guy wants to run for president.

34:58.013 --> 34:59.722
Oh, so you're hiding, I see.

34:59.890 --> 35:02.475
He thinks Moby Dick is
a venereal disease.

35:02.642 --> 35:04.560
Well, that's what I need. Claire.

35:04.728 --> 35:06.353
[JOHN LAUGHING]

35:06.521 --> 35:08.439
Sorry to interrupt.

35:08.607 --> 35:11.025
-Christina wants to talk to you.
-Fun's over.

35:13.862 --> 35:15.196
-Yeah.
-Funny.

35:15.363 --> 35:17.865
CLEARY: Franklin!
-What a great guy.

35:18.784 --> 35:20.743
You are a big hit at this wedding.

35:20.911 --> 35:23.954
Well, everyone's so nice. It's easy.

35:26.291 --> 35:29.001
-They're all full of shit.
-What?

35:29.169 --> 35:31.337
Half of these people are here
because of my dad.

35:31.505 --> 35:35.174
They're all just, you know,
suckling at the power teat.

35:35.383 --> 35:38.928
No, no. Come on, they're here
because they want to believe...

35:39.095 --> 35:42.097
...they're in the presence of true love.
That's why people come to weddings.

35:42.265 --> 35:45.392
Because they wanna believe in true love.

35:45.560 --> 35:46.811
What's true love?

35:48.730 --> 35:52.608
True love is your soul's recognition
of its counterpoint in another.

35:57.322 --> 36:00.491
Well, it's a little cheesy, but I like it.

36:00.659 --> 36:02.243
I saw it on a bumper sticker.

36:02.410 --> 36:03.744
[CHUCKLES]

36:04.412 --> 36:06.205
-So you gonna give a toast?
-Yes.

36:06.373 --> 36:08.415
-You nervous?
-Mmm, little bit, um.

36:08.583 --> 36:11.585
-What are you gonna say?
-Would you...?

36:13.255 --> 36:16.507
-You keep it in your cleavage.
-Nowhere else to put it.

36:16.675 --> 36:20.886
Normally, I'm not very good at these things,
but I think this one's pretty good.

36:21.054 --> 36:23.013
"I never thought my sister
would find someone...

36:23.181 --> 36:25.850
...who cared about what other people
thought as much as she did...

36:26.017 --> 36:28.269
-...until I met Craig"?
-Yes.

36:28.436 --> 36:30.688
That's funny.
That's funny because it's true.

36:30.856 --> 36:32.356
You know, people like funny.

36:32.524 --> 36:35.359
I know. But the whole
funny-because-it's-true bit...

36:35.527 --> 36:37.903
...only works if the truth
is a small thing.

36:38.071 --> 36:41.115
Like, "Everyone knows
Jennifer likes to shop, ha, ha, ha."

36:41.283 --> 36:43.617
You're better off going
with something from the heart.

36:43.785 --> 36:45.786
I think that people are gonna like this.

36:45.954 --> 36:47.621
I think you're gonna hear crickets.

36:47.789 --> 36:49.623
-I think you're wrong.
-Sounds of silence.

36:49.791 --> 36:52.167
-Nope. Mm-mm.
-Okay, go walk the plank.

36:52.335 --> 36:54.253
-I'm sticking to it.
-Go ahead.

36:54.421 --> 36:57.798
Hey, meet me at the back of the room.
I'll be waiting to say, "I told you so."

37:01.720 --> 37:03.304
Good luck.

37:03.471 --> 37:09.226
And so, after my ninth stint
in rehab, um, Craig....

37:09.394 --> 37:11.061
Oh, Craig.

37:11.229 --> 37:15.190
Craig was the only one
who still believed in me.

37:15.358 --> 37:17.276
Been sober now for eight months.

37:17.444 --> 37:18.736
[CHUCKLING]

37:18.904 --> 37:23.240
And, uh, I thank God every day...

37:23.408 --> 37:26.827
...for sending me a friend like Craig.

37:26.995 --> 37:28.871
I love you, man.

37:29.039 --> 37:31.040
[PEOPLE CLAPPING]

37:40.008 --> 37:41.467
[CLAIRE CLEARS THROAT]

37:44.763 --> 37:47.264
I never thought my sister
would find someone who cared about...

37:47.432 --> 37:50.684
...what other people thought
as much as she did until I met Craig.

37:56.816 --> 37:58.150
Uh....

37:58.318 --> 38:01.695
As you all know,
my sister and Craig are both lawyers...

38:01.863 --> 38:04.490
...at big law firms in New York.

38:04.866 --> 38:07.868
But that's not the only thing
they have in common. Um....

38:08.036 --> 38:10.704
They both like the color green...

38:10.872 --> 38:14.291
...like Craig's eyes and money.

38:18.964 --> 38:20.881
Um, heh....

38:32.560 --> 38:35.813
You know, someone once told me that...

38:35.981 --> 38:38.107
...true love is...

38:38.274 --> 38:41.318
...the soul's recognition
of its counterpoint in another.

38:43.363 --> 38:46.907
And I think that
that's a very rare thing in this world.

38:48.827 --> 38:51.495
And I think it's something to be valued.

38:51.663 --> 38:55.124
And I'm just really happy
that my big sister's found it.

38:55.291 --> 38:57.835
Congratulations, Chris.

38:58.086 --> 38:59.586
[MOUTHING]
Thank you.

38:59.754 --> 39:01.714
[PEOPLE CLAPPING]

39:10.932 --> 39:12.266
Ah!

39:12.434 --> 39:15.519
-That was amazing!
-It was really great.

39:15.812 --> 39:19.314
We should probably head back
so they're not looking for us.

39:19.482 --> 39:22.276
I always knew my first time
would be on a beach.

39:23.653 --> 39:25.612
First time?

39:28.658 --> 39:30.034
You were a virgin?

39:30.201 --> 39:31.744
-Mm-hm.
-Wow.

39:31.911 --> 39:35.372
Jeremy, we're gonna
be so happy together.

39:36.416 --> 39:37.583
I love you.

39:37.751 --> 39:39.752
-I'm sorry?
-I love you.

39:49.679 --> 39:51.597
CLAIRE: You totally saved me.
-No.

39:51.765 --> 39:54.141
-Yes.
-Claire, come on. Come on.

39:55.852 --> 39:58.187
Oh, baby, you were awesome.

39:58.354 --> 39:59.980
-No.
-Listen to me, awesome.

40:00.148 --> 40:01.565
Okay.

40:01.733 --> 40:04.401
John, this is my boyfriend, Sack.

40:04.569 --> 40:06.612
-Hey, fella.
-How you doing?

40:06.780 --> 40:08.655
-Listen, we gotta go meet the Schreibers.
-Okay.

40:08.823 --> 40:10.074
It was great to meet you.

40:10.241 --> 40:11.658
[WHISPERING]
Thank you.

40:14.245 --> 40:15.788
Boom, I gotcha.

40:15.955 --> 40:16.997
[LAUGHING]

40:17.165 --> 40:20.000
-How you doing?
-Oh, great. Good to see you.

40:20.418 --> 40:22.002
I gotta get out of here, pronto.

40:22.170 --> 40:24.588
-I got a Stage 5 clinger.
-No, no, I need more time.

40:25.131 --> 40:28.550
Did you hear what I just said to you?
Stage 5? Virgin? Clinger?

40:28.718 --> 40:31.887
Let's go, I'm gonna start the car.
I'm serious, let's go.

40:34.015 --> 40:35.641
I don't think you appreciate the urgency.

40:35.809 --> 40:38.393
Not only is she a virgin,
she's totally off the reservation.

40:38.561 --> 40:40.771
I'm terrified of this broad.

40:40.939 --> 40:44.274
-There you are.
-Hey, Gloria, wow.

40:44.442 --> 40:46.985
What a coincidence, I was just singing
your praises. This is John Ryan.

40:47.153 --> 40:48.403
GLORIA: Oh, hi.
-Yeah.

40:48.571 --> 40:51.698
My family and a few friends, we're all
going back to our place on the shore...

40:51.866 --> 40:53.951
...and it would be so great
if you guys came.

40:54.119 --> 40:55.202
Really?

40:55.370 --> 40:56.787
-Sounds sort of wonderful.
-I am--

40:56.955 --> 40:58.705
Well, it does, it sounds very nice.

40:58.873 --> 41:00.707
And I'm flattered that you would
think of me...

41:00.875 --> 41:02.876
...to include me in something like that.
Thank you.

41:03.044 --> 41:06.547
It kills me however to have to tell you
I'm sorry, I just--

41:06.714 --> 41:08.715
-Timing's no good. I can't make it.
-Why?

41:08.883 --> 41:11.510
-It's gonna be so much fun.
-It's gonna be so much fun.

41:11.678 --> 41:13.846
I'm sure it will be fun
for the people that are going.

41:14.013 --> 41:17.641
I unfortunately can't go. I don't have--
I only have this monkey suit.

41:17.809 --> 41:20.185
-I don't have any clothes.
-No, we have everything you need.

41:20.353 --> 41:23.063
-Problem solved. Problem solved.
-The problem's not solved.

41:23.231 --> 41:25.399
-Deal us in.
-Oh, cool, cool, cool.

41:25.567 --> 41:27.192
I'm gonna run and find my dad.

41:27.360 --> 41:28.819
Don't ask your dad.
Don't ask your--

41:28.987 --> 41:31.905
-The train's going. We gotta get on.
-Why not just feed me to the lions?

41:32.073 --> 41:34.074
-What?
-Step on my head when I'm drowning.

41:34.242 --> 41:35.951
-What?
-What do you mean, what?

41:36.119 --> 41:37.828
John, this is completely
against the rules.

41:37.996 --> 41:40.497
You have a wedding and a reception
to seal the deal. Period.

41:40.665 --> 41:42.416
-There's no overtime. No.
-Oh, no overtime?

41:42.584 --> 41:44.209
What about the Chang wedding
three years ago?

41:44.377 --> 41:46.962
-Oh, that's bullshit.
-Yeah, thought I forgot about that.

41:47.130 --> 41:49.506
Two a.m., you dragged me 50 miles
to watch you and some chick...

41:49.674 --> 41:52.384
...play mahjong with her grandmother
at a retirement home.

41:52.552 --> 41:54.303
-Yeah, completely different situation.
-How?

41:54.470 --> 41:57.431
What do you mean, how?
She was a very, very family-oriented girl.

41:57.599 --> 41:59.266
She was very into her grandmother.

41:59.434 --> 42:01.476
-Give me a break.
-That was my first Asian!

42:03.771 --> 42:05.439
-You better lock it up.
-You better lock it up.

42:05.607 --> 42:08.609
-No, you lock it up. Lock it up.
-You lock it up. Lock it up.

42:08.776 --> 42:12.279
Please. It would mean
so much to me. Please.

42:12.447 --> 42:14.031
Look at the way he's looking at me.

42:14.199 --> 42:16.283
He doesn't like me.
He's the secretary of the treasury.

42:16.451 --> 42:18.702
To be honest with you,
my taxes aren't exactly in line.

42:18.870 --> 42:21.455
-You're being paranoid.
-He's threatened by the way I dance.

42:21.623 --> 42:23.957
Damn it. Why'd I have to
go showing off like that?

42:24.125 --> 42:26.293
Now I'm all over his radar. Stupid.

42:26.461 --> 42:27.878
You're not that good a dancer.

42:28.046 --> 42:30.631
Oh, please. You and I both know
I'm a phenomenal dancer.

42:30.798 --> 42:33.342
Now I know you're lying.
You'll do anything to get me to go...

42:33.509 --> 42:36.053
...even if I have to walk
right into the lion's den.

42:36.221 --> 42:37.971
Gloria, come on!

42:38.139 --> 42:40.849
You know I'm not gonna give in
to this kind of behavior.

42:41.017 --> 42:43.143
She's like a kid at Toys "R" Us.
I can't be around it.

42:43.311 --> 42:45.354
Oh, get off your high horse.
Stop judging people.

42:45.521 --> 42:47.522
You take off the white wig
and you stop judging me.

42:47.690 --> 42:49.858
I don't want to be around
someone who's a nut job.

42:50.026 --> 42:52.569
-I need alone time with her.
-You wanna hang out with Claire...

42:52.737 --> 42:55.322
...the boyfriend and Sybil,
by all means. I'm not going.

42:55.490 --> 42:57.741
I'll lay it out for you
in chapter and verse: You're going.

42:57.909 --> 43:01.328
Let me break it down for you,
I'll hold your hand like a small child:

43:01.496 --> 43:02.537
-I'm not going.
-You are.

43:02.705 --> 43:04.915
-You can go if you want.
-You're gonna be a team player.

43:05.083 --> 43:07.167
JEREMY: No, I'm not.
-He'd love you to come.

43:07.335 --> 43:10.837
-Yes. Yes! Baba ganoush!
-Well--

43:11.005 --> 43:12.506
GLORIA:
Baba ganou!

43:25.853 --> 43:29.523
SACK:
Okay, okay. Home sweet home.

43:29.691 --> 43:32.192
KATHLEEN:
Thank you, Sack. Thank you.

43:33.069 --> 43:34.945
JOHN: You okay?
-Yeah. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

43:35.113 --> 43:37.364
JOHN:
Come here, come here.

43:37.532 --> 43:41.201
Are you okay? I'm gonna need 1 00 percent
of Jeremy and you're looking a little weird.

43:41.369 --> 43:44.955
She took me below deck for 45 minutes.
I don't have any bodily fluids left in me.

43:45.123 --> 43:47.040
Gentlemen, everything okay?

43:47.208 --> 43:48.667
-Great. Yep.
SACK: Great?

43:48.835 --> 43:52.379
You know, we were thinking about
a little game of touch football, you know?

43:52.880 --> 43:55.299
-Yeah?
-Cleary family tradition.

43:55.466 --> 43:56.842
A little pigskin, why not?

43:57.010 --> 43:58.927
CLEARY: Great.
-Don't forget to stretch, guys.

43:59.095 --> 44:01.054
We're gonna be on the field in 1 0.

44:01.347 --> 44:03.181
CLAIRE:
I'm open, I'm open!

44:06.269 --> 44:09.896
SACK:
There you go. Nice, nice, nice.

44:10.064 --> 44:11.106
There you go.

44:31.002 --> 44:33.045
Clothes fit.

44:33.212 --> 44:36.465
I'm not even gonna say it,
but you know I'm upset.

44:36.632 --> 44:39.509
I know you are.
I think you look good.

44:40.386 --> 44:42.596
You know I don't look good.

44:43.639 --> 44:46.641
GLORIA:
Hey, honey! I'm over here!

44:47.518 --> 44:49.353
Are you ready?
Are you ready for some football?

44:49.520 --> 44:51.438
You want the noise brought on you?
Here it comes.

44:51.606 --> 44:53.607
-The what?
MAN: The noise brought on you.

44:53.775 --> 44:55.609
-Here it comes.
-Just hike the ball, nut job.

44:55.777 --> 45:00.072
Ready! Set! Hut! Hut! Hike!

45:00.239 --> 45:02.699
One Mississippi, two Mississippi,
three Mississippi.

45:02.867 --> 45:04.743
CLAIRE:
Over here! Me, me, me!

45:06.079 --> 45:07.537
[GRUNTING]

45:07.705 --> 45:08.789
MAN:
Yes!

45:08.956 --> 45:10.123
-Wow.
-Whoo!

45:10.291 --> 45:12.417
Yes! Crab cakes and football!

45:12.585 --> 45:14.378
-That's what Maryland does!
CLEARY: Nice one.

45:15.088 --> 45:16.296
[GRUNTS]

45:16.964 --> 45:18.173
-A little out of shape?
-Yeah.

45:18.341 --> 45:19.841
[CHUCKLES]

45:20.134 --> 45:21.676
-Way to bring it.
SACK: Anticipate that rush.

45:21.844 --> 45:23.261
-I saw you had it.
-Hey, shut up!

45:23.429 --> 45:25.430
-You gotta anticipate that rush.
-Of course I do.

45:25.598 --> 45:27.724
SACK: You did a great job.
JEREMY: What happened, Toast?

45:27.892 --> 45:29.476
I think he's on steroids.

45:29.644 --> 45:31.770
It was like trying to cover
a fucking racehorse.

45:31.938 --> 45:33.021
[GRUNTING]

45:33.189 --> 45:36.233
-Get it up! Get it up!
-Well, don't worry about it.

45:36.401 --> 45:40.112
-We'll burn them with the post.
-No, no. No, I got a better idea.

45:40.279 --> 45:42.572
Look, I want you to fake the post...

45:42.740 --> 45:45.325
...throw an interception to Claire,
get her to feel good.

45:45.493 --> 45:47.452
Gets her involved.
You think you can do that?

45:47.620 --> 45:50.705
John, I was first team, all-state.
I can put the ball wherever I want to.

45:50.873 --> 45:55.293
I'll make it rain out here.
All right, guys, bring it in. Blue 1 7!

45:56.212 --> 45:58.672
Blue 1 7! Red 7!

45:58.840 --> 46:01.341
-Oh, you're gonna cover me?
-Like white on rice.

46:01.509 --> 46:04.344
All right, I like my odds here.
I'm gonna give you a little warning:

46:04.512 --> 46:06.263
-I'm going downtown.
-Hot route!

46:06.431 --> 46:08.640
Red 7, Red 7, Red 7!

46:08.808 --> 46:11.309
Look for me in the end zone,
I'll be the guy holding the ball.

46:11.477 --> 46:13.186
-John! Red 7!
-What?

46:13.354 --> 46:16.106
-I don't know what "Red 7" means.
-Hot route!

46:16.274 --> 46:17.691
I don't-- What is "hot route"?

46:18.192 --> 46:20.944
Will you just go stand
on the other side, please?

46:21.112 --> 46:22.612
CLAIRE:
Are you running away from me?

46:22.780 --> 46:25.866
JOHN: No. I'm just getting over here.
CLAIRE: You scared?

46:26.242 --> 46:27.951
-Down!
-Come on.

46:28.119 --> 46:32.372
Ready, down, set!
Hut! Hut! Hut! Hike!

46:33.875 --> 46:35.167
GLORIA:
Go, Jeremy!

46:35.334 --> 46:37.669
Hey, yo! Hit me! Hit me!

46:39.005 --> 46:40.046
Booyah!

46:40.214 --> 46:42.716
That's what we call a "Sack lunch"!
Yum, yum, yum, yum.

46:44.302 --> 46:45.510
Ow, burn.

46:46.345 --> 46:47.929
[SCREAMING]

46:48.181 --> 46:49.723
Big tree fall hard, right?

46:49.891 --> 46:52.726
How many fingers I got up?
Come on, Pepe, how many fingers I got up?

46:52.894 --> 46:55.020
Oh, come on, I got four.
Okay, here's five.

46:55.188 --> 46:58.899
Man down! We got a man down.
You okay?

46:59.066 --> 47:01.026
Hey, is your brother okay?

47:01.194 --> 47:03.653
-What? Ah, he's fine.
-I can't breathe.

47:03.821 --> 47:05.572
SACK: What's that?
-I can't breathe.

47:05.740 --> 47:08.658
No, no, no, I think he's really hurt.

47:08.826 --> 47:11.453
Well, serves him right after that throw.

47:11.621 --> 47:13.413
Hey. Baba ganoush.

47:13.581 --> 47:15.790
I don't know what
got into me, secretary, I just--

47:15.958 --> 47:19.836
I do. Five generations
of Lodge family breeding.

47:20.004 --> 47:21.963
[GROWLING AND CHUCKLING]

47:22.256 --> 47:25.217
-Your father used to pull the same stunt...
-I can't breathe.

47:25.384 --> 47:27.385
-...when we were your age.
-I can't breathe.

47:27.553 --> 47:28.762
You okay?

47:28.930 --> 47:31.056
[WHISPERING]
Great. You threw it perfectly.

47:31.224 --> 47:33.099
Come on, get up.

47:33.267 --> 47:35.310
-Don't oversell it.
-I'm not selling anything.

47:35.478 --> 47:39.231
Come on, stop milking it.
You make us look like a bunch of pussies.

47:39.398 --> 47:41.608
Jeremy. Sit this play out.

47:42.026 --> 47:44.152
Todd, come on in.

47:45.029 --> 47:46.613
You must be joking.

47:46.781 --> 47:50.325
It wouldn't kill you to play
some competitive sports...

47:50.493 --> 47:51.910
...once in a while, would it?

47:52.078 --> 47:53.787
Oh, would that make you love me?

47:53.955 --> 47:55.705
Pfft. Jesus.

47:56.499 --> 47:59.292
Hey, Jeremy, Red Moon Dog 7-11.

47:59.460 --> 48:01.294
Forty-two, 30-teen.

48:01.462 --> 48:03.171
Hut one! Hut two!

48:03.339 --> 48:04.464
Blitz!

48:04.632 --> 48:06.925
-Oh! Ah!
-Jeremy!

48:07.301 --> 48:09.052
[GRUNTING]

48:09.220 --> 48:10.637
[GASPING]

48:10.805 --> 48:12.347
-That looked like it hurt.
-Ooh.

48:12.515 --> 48:14.099
